      <description>&lt;p&gt;Source: &lt;a href=&#34;https://divyaprabandham.koyil.org/index.php/2017/06/mudhal-thiruvandhadhi/&#34;&gt;TW&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;SrI: SrImathE SatakOpAya nama: SrImathE rAmAnujAya nama: SrImath varavaramunayE nama:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://divyaprabandham.koyil.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/paramapadhanathan.jpg&#34;&gt;&lt;figure class=&#34;&#34;&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;a href=&#34;https://divyaprabandham.koyil.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/paramapadhanathan.jpg&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://divyaprabandham.koyil.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/paramapadhanathan.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;&#34; title=&#34;&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &#xA;&#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://divyaprabandham.koyil.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/poigaiazhwar.jpg&#34;&gt;&lt;figure class=&#34;&#34;&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;a href=&#34;https://divyaprabandham.koyil.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/poigaiazhwar.jpg&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://divyaprabandham.koyil.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/poigaiazhwar.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;&#34; title=&#34;&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &#xA;&#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;e-book – &lt;a href=&#34;https://1drv.ms/b/s!AiNzc-LF3uwyhHC79bdFyUWrJpC0&#34;&gt;https://1drv.ms/b/s!AiNzc-LF3uwyhHC79bdFyUWrJpC0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://acharyas.koyil.org/index.php/poigai-azhwar/&#34;&gt;poygai AzhwAr&lt;/a&gt;, the first among the mudhalAzhwArgaL (first 3 AzhwArs namely &lt;a href=&#34;http://acharyas.koyil.org/index.php/poigai-azhwar/&#34;&gt;poygai AzhwAr&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;http://acharyas.koyil.org/index.php/bhuthaththazhwar/&#34;&gt;bhUthaththAzhwAr&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;http://acharyas.koyil.org/index.php/peyazhwar/&#34;&gt;pEyAzhwAr&lt;/a&gt;) divined a beautiful prabandham named mudhal thiruvandhAdhi. This is part of the iyaRpA section of the dhivya prabandham. iyaRpA is generally recited during puRappAdu (ceremonial procession of uthsava deity of emperumAn).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A beautiful correlation among the four thiruvandhAdhis is highlighted in the vyAkhyAnams. Let us see that briefly before we proceed to immerse ourselves in this prabandham.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
